    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-08-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-08-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="426"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d426">
                <head>No. 427.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Sickles</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-08-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 18, 1872</date>. (Received August
                        26.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 411.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The following is the text of a cable message
                    forwarded to-day from this legation: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p rend="flushleft">“<hi rend="smallcaps">Hamilton Fish</hi>, <hi
                                rend="italic">Secretary of State, Washington:</hi>
                        </p>
                        <p>“King has signed regulations enforcing emancipation law in Cuba and Porto
                            Rico.</p>
                        <p rend="right">“SICKLES.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I have reason to hope, from the repeated assurances given me by the minister of
                    the colonies, Mr. Gasset y Artime, that these regulations will appear to have
                    been framed with a sincere purpose to execute the law. If published in the
                    Gazette, I shall lose no time in forwarding a copy for your perusal. In any
                    event 1 presume a copy will be given to me, although perhaps unofficially, as
                    the minister of the colonies kindly intimated a wish a few days ago that I would
                    read the draught of the document which was then under consideration.</p>
                <p>My impression is that, if the election for the congress appointed to meet on the
                    1st of September proximo prove favorable to the liberal party, the law of 1870
                    will be made a more comprehensive and satisfactory measure.</p>
                <p>Following the tenor of your repeated instructions, I shall regard it as my duty
                    to renew the representations I have so often made in the name of the President
                    on this subject.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>D. E. SICKLES.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
